<section xml:id="Joint-Variation"   xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude"><title>Joint Variation</title>

<subsection><title>1. Evaluate a function of two variables</title>

<introduction><p>We evaluate a function of two variables just as we do any other function: by substituting the given values for the variables.</p></introduction>

<subsubsection><title>Examples</title>

<example><statement><p>Evaluate <m>~f(x,y) = 1.6x^2 + 2.4y~</m> for <m>x=24</m> and <m>y=300</m>.</p></statement>

<solution><p>We substitute <m>\alert{240}</m> for <m>x</m> and <m>\alert{300}</m> for <m>y</m>.
    <md><mrow>f(\alert{24}, \alert{300}) \amp = 1.6(\alert{24}^2) + 2.4(\alert{300})</mrow>
        <mrow> \amp = 1.6(576) + 2.4(300) = 921.6 + 720 = 1641.6</mrow></md></p></solution></example>

<example><statement><p><m>h(s,t) = 12s^{2/3}t^{1/4}</m>.  Evaluate <m>h(35,60).</m> Round your answer to thousandths.</p></statement>

<solution><p>We substitute <m>\alert{35}</m> for <m>s</m> and <m>\alert{60}</m> for <m>t</m>.
    <md><mrow>h(\alert{35}, \alert{60}) \amp = 12(\alert{35}^{2/3})(\alert{60}^{1/4})</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = 12(10.700)(2.783) = 357.353</mrow></md></p></solution></example>
</subsubsection>

<subsubsection><title>Exercises</title>

<exercise><statement><p>Evaluate <m>~g(a,b) = \dfrac{4a^3}{b^{1/2}}~</m> for <m>a=8</m> and <m>b=12</m>.</p></statement>
<answer><p><m>591.207</m></p></answer></exercise>

